types of new()

Assume pointer declaration:
	int* _arr;

1)	_arr = new int[n]
	vs
2)	new (&_arr[i]) int();


1)	_arr = new int[n]

	- regular new operator for array allocation.
	- Allocates memory for an array of n elements of type int
	- Each element in the array is constructed in its allocated memory. 
	- The memory is zero-initialized 
	- Returns a pointer to the beginning of the array.

2)	new (&_arr[i]) int();
	-  This uses placement new operator.
	-  Constructs a int object at the specific memory location pointed to by &_arr[i].
	-  this assumes memory has been previously allocated.
	- This does not return a pointer to a newly allocated memory region;
		 it operates on existing memory.
